    {
      "id": "cultural_w3",
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Kulturelt hjørne — Families in Denmark",
      "content": "Danish families come in many shapes and sizes. The concept of 'kernefamilien' (the nuclear family) — two parents and their children — is common, but so are 'regnbuefamilier' (rainbow families) and 'sammenbragte familier' (blended families). Denmark has one of the world's highest rates of children born outside of marriage — over half of all children are born to unmarried parents, though many of these couples live together in stable partnerships ('papirløst samlevende'). The word 'kæreste' is gender-neutral and means boyfriend, girlfriend, or partner — Danish does not distinguish. When addressing older relatives, Danes typically use first names rather than formal titles — calling your grandmother 'farmor' (father's mother) or 'mormor' (mother's mother) rather than a generic 'grandmother'."
    }
